{"name": "plm-cs", "metadata": {"name": "plm-cs", "version": "1.1", "classifiers": ["License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Natural Language :: English", "Operating System :: OS Independent", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Topic :: Scientific/Engineering :: Artificial Intelligence", "Topic :: Scientific/Engineering :: Bio-Informatics"], "home_page": "https://github.com/doorpro/predict-chemical-shifts-from-protein-sequence.git", "license": null, "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": ["torch", "torchaudio", "torchvision", "fair-esm", "numpy", "biopython", "pandas"], "summary": "Protein chemical shift prediction based on Protein Language Model", "upload_time": 1734421769}, "documentation": ["## PLM-CS  \n## Predict protein chemical shifts from sequence\n\n\n![image](/image/image1.png)\n### Train your model\nIf you want to train your own PLM-CS model, this repository provides all the tools and data. Just follow these steps.\n\n\n#### Training set\nWe provide the complete training set data in [RefDB training dataset](./dataset/RefDB_test_remove). Each file in this folder is in nmrstar format, and each file corresponds to a protein. All proteins contained in the *SHIFTX test* are removed from it.\n#### Training set processing\nFor convenience, the reasoning process of the ESM model is separate from the training process of our regression model. Therefore, we first use ESM-650M to process the data. Change the \"save_path\" in [esm_process.py](./esm_process.py) to your own path. A tensordataset containing the training data will be generated.\n#### Train\nModify the path in the [train.py](./train.py) to your own parh. Also, be aware that this can only train a model of one type of atom at a time.\n#### Training parameters\nDifferent atom types correspond to different optimizer strategies.You can modify the corresponding parameters in the [train.py](./train.py) according to your trained model. The default number of steps for an iteration is 20,000, but you can change it to 5,000 to achieve very close performance while reducing training time\nparameters     | C\u03b1 | C\u03b2 | C | H\u03b1 | H | N\n-------- |--|--|--|--|--|--|\nlearning rate|0.02|5e-4|0.002|0.01|5e-4|5e-4\noptimizer| SGD|Adam|Adam|SGD|Adam|Adam\n#### Evaluate\n\n### Use PLM-CS through python SDK\n\n\n"], "modules": [{"name": "plm-cs.CS_predict", "documentation": ["!/usr/bin/env python", "-*- coding = utf-8 -*-", "@Time : 2024/8/7 20:24", "@Author : ZhuHe", "@File : LinearModel.py", "@Software : PyCharm", "@File : CS_predict.py", "@desc:"], "functions": [{"name": "plm-cs.CS_predict.predict_from_seq", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "protein_sequence", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "result_file", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "plm-cs.CS_predict.main", "asynchronous": false, "params": [], "returns": null, "documentation": []}], "variables": [{"name": "plm-cs.CS_predict.current_file_directory", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "plm-cs.CS_predict.config_path", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "plm-cs.CS_predict.config", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name": "plm-cs.model", "documentation": ["coding:utf-8\n@software:\n@Time:2024/7/30 22:15\n@Author:door"], "functions": [{"name": "plm-cs.model.attention", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "q", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "k", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "v", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "d_k", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "mask", "type": null, "default": "..."}, {"name": "dropout", "type": null, "default": "..."}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "plm-cs.model.get_clones", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "module", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "N", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "plm-cs.model.create_target_mask", "asynchronous": false